Ah, [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), another testament to humanity's tireless efforts to pave over everything. A [state highway](/State_highway) in [Jersey City, New Jersey](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey), destined to carry the weary and the desperate eastward. Its journey begins, rather dramatically, from the concrete embrace of the [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway), hovering precariously over the architectural marvel that is [Tonnele Circle](/Tonnele_Circle). From there, it plunges towards the abyss of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel), a subterranean artery beneath the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River), disgorging its contents into the glorious chaos of [New York City](/New_York_City). One might almost call it a pilgrimage, if pilgrimages involved this much traffic.

This isn't just one road, mind you; it's a layered confection, a two-tiered cake of asphalt and frustration. The [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) (NJDOT), in its infinite wisdom, dissects this beast into two distinct entities, as if that makes it less confusing. There's the lower roadway, a modest 1.45-mile (2.33 km) stretch, officially designated as plain old Route 139. It snakes between [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9) (US 1/9) over Tonnele Circle and the rather more imposing [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) (I-78) at Jersey Avenue. Then, for those who prefer the high ground, there’s the upper roadway, a mere 0.83-mile (1.34 km) ribbon known as Route 139U, or, more charmingly, Hoboken Avenue. This elevated path commences its brief existence from [County Route 501](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)) (John F. Kennedy Boulevard), eventually condescending to join its lower sibling as part of the 12th Street [Viaduct](/Viaduct), a structure that, like all good things, concludes at Jersey Avenue.

Lest you forget its venerable age, the lower roadway has been deemed worthy of a place on both the [federal](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) and [NJ state](/New_Jersey_Register_of_Historic_Places) registers of historic places since 2005. A monument to... well, traffic. Its eastern 1.32 miles (2.12 km) are less a road and more an extension of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) itself, a path it shares, quite intimately, in a [concurrency](/Concurrency_(road)) with [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey). This final stretch is a peculiar [one-way pair](/One-way_pair) utilizing 12th Street for eastbound pilgrims and 14th Street for those less fortunate souls heading westbound. When you tally up these segmented existences, the grand total length of Route 139 unfurls to a staggering 2.77 miles (4.46 km). A journey of profound significance, I'm sure.

This particular stretch of asphalt, now known as [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), didn't always carry such a distinctive, if rather bland, moniker. In its youth, it was merely the northernmost appendage of the ambitious [Route 1 Extension](/New_Jersey_Route_25). Then, in the glorious [1927 renumbering](/1927_renumbering_(New_Jersey)) – a period of bureaucratic self-indulgence if ever there was one – [Route 25](/New_Jersey_Route_25) swept in, usurping the identity of Route 1. But like a poorly planned sequel, this change was short-lived. By the [1953 renumbering](/1953_New_Jersey_state_highway_renumbering), Route 25 was unceremoniously reverted to [U.S. Route 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_New_Jersey), which, having already found a more glamorous way to cross the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River) via the grand opening of the [George Washington Bridge](/George_Washington_Bridge) in 1931, had no real need for this humble segment. Consequently, the portion of Route 25 extending from the [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway) over [Tonnele Circle](/Tonnele_Circle) to the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) found itself rebranded as U.S. Route 1/9 Business. A temporary identity, a placeholder in the grand scheme of things. It wasn't until the 1990s, a decade of questionable fashion choices and even more questionable highway planning, that U.S. Route 1/9 Business finally shed its cumbersome title and embraced its current, rather unremarkable, identity as [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)). The endless cycle of renaming, truly fascinating.

Predictably, by 2005, the inevitable decay of infrastructure demanded attention. The [NJDOT](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) embarked on a 'rehabilitation program' – a polite term for patching up what should have been built to last – for both the lower and upper levels of this highway. A five-year endeavor, the renovation of the 12th Street and 14th Street [viaducts](/Viaduct) was finally 'completed' in 2010. One wonders what exactly constitutes 'completion' in the world of roadworks. As for the upper roadway, encompassing the Hoboken Avenue Viaduct and the Conrail Viaduct on the lower roadway, its renovation was optimistically projected for completion by 2016. Because nothing says 'efficiency' like a highway project with a moving target for its finish line.

## Route description

[[Signage on the 14th Street Viaduct at the western terminus of the concurrency of I-78 and Route 139 in Jersey City]]
To truly grasp the essence of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), one must first accept its inherent schizophrenia. It’s not merely a road; it's a trinity of asphalt, a hydra-headed beast with three distinct, yet inconveniently interconnected, personalities. We have the upper level, the lower level, and the final, unavoidable embrace of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) approach – which, for administrative purposes, is simply known as the [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) [concurrency](/Concurrency_(road))). The [NJDOT](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation), in its tireless quest for clarity, officially delineates the lower and upper levels as separate, independent highways. The lower is the 'true' Route 139, with a small, almost apologetic, note that it eventually consents to coincide with [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey). The upper level, meanwhile, is designated as Route 139U, a designation rarely, if ever, seen on actual road signs. Because why make things easy when you can make them... layered? [1] [2] [3]

### Lower level

The lower level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) presents itself as a four-lane [freeway](/Controlled-access_highway), a seemingly straightforward conduit for the masses. Its genesis, or western end, lies at [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9), effectively a continuation of the monolithic [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway) as it gracefully, or perhaps grudgingly, sails over [Tonnele Circle](/Tonnele_Circle). [1] For those westbound travelers with a specific destination in mind, a direct ramp, affectionately dubbed the Tonnele Circle Viaduct, offers an escape. It arcs over the circle itself, directing traffic towards southbound [U.S. Route 1/9 Truck](/U.S._Route_1-9_Truck), a path that swiftly, almost impatiently, leads to [Route 7](/New_Jersey_Route_7) and, ultimately, the embrace of [Interstate 280](/Interstate_280_(New_Jersey)). Meanwhile, northbound U.S. Route 1/9 Truck navigates the same circle, connecting to the eastbound flow of traffic. [4]

The skyway's grand illusion of perpetual motion soon dissolves, giving way to eastbound and westbound ramps that descend into a rather abrupt [cut](/Cut_(earthmoving)) carved into the ancient [Bergen Hill](/Bergen_Hill). Here, the four-lane highway ducks beneath the imposing presence of [John F. Kennedy Boulevard](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)). [1] [4] The road then executes a subtle turn to the southeast, seemingly to avoid the overhead entanglement of Conrail's [National Docks Branch](/National_Docks_Branch) and the [Long Dock Tunnel](/Long_Dock_Tunnel), which span the ghostly remains of the [Bergen Arches](/Bergen_Arches), an abandoned [Erie Railroad](/Erie_Railroad) right-of-way. [5]

What follows is perhaps the most aptly named section: the highway plunges into an enclosed open cut, a subterranean passage beneath its own upper level, a literal underbelly of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)). [4] This segment, traversing the formidable [Hudson Palisades](/Hudson_Palisades), is known, without a hint of irony, as the Depressed Highway. [6] [7] One can almost feel the weight of the earth, and the existential dread, above. Despite its subterranean nature, this covered roadway boasts a rather quaint 'natural ventilation' system, featuring wide openings on the south side of the eastbound lanes – presumably to allow a glimpse of the parallel Bergen Arches right-of-way to the south – and a series of ventilation bays strategically placed over the westbound lanes. [8] Finally, after its brief foray into the depths, the road re-emerges into the light, passing under [Palisade Avenue](/Palisade_Avenue_(Hudson_Palisades)). Here, it performs a final, decisive split into two independent [viaducts](/Viaducts) – one for eastbound traffic, one for westbound – before gracefully merging with [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) just west of Jersey Avenue, signalling the imminent approach to the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel). [1] [4]

### Upper level

[[Sign designating the upper level of Route 139 as State Highway]]
For those who prefer a less 'depressed' existence, there’s the upper level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), a fleeting moment of elevation also known by the rather generic 'State Highway' or the more specific 'Hoboken Avenue Viaduct'. [5] [8] Its journey commences at an intersection with [County Route 501](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)) (Kennedy Boulevard), a vital artery connecting to the distant realms of [Bayonne](/Bayonne,_New_Jersey) and [Union City](/Union_City,_New_Jersey). From this bustling nexus, the road gracefully sweeps southeastward, carving its way through a tapestry of urban residential and commercial areas. Initially, it presents itself as a four-lane undivided thoroughfare, a brief moment of democratic simplicity before the inevitable complexities arise. Its first notable encounter is with Collard Street. [2] [9]

Beyond this point, the route undergoes a transformation, becoming a four-lane divided road. This division is not merely aesthetic; it's a functional separation, maintained by those rather curious ventilation bays that also serve the lower roadway. Here, the eastbound lanes assert their dominance, literally running *above* the lower level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), a subtle hierarchy in concrete. [8] This elevated pathway continues its traverse, acting as a crucial boundary between the charmingly named [the Heights](/The_Heights,_Jersey_City) district to the north and the perpetually bustling [Journal Square](/Journal_Square) district to the south. [9] Along its course, it condescends to intersect with a series of other local arteries, including County Route 646 (St. Pauls Avenue), [County Route 617](/County_Route_617_(Hudson_County,_New_Jersey)) (Summit Avenue), [County Route 663](/County_Route_663_(Hudson_County,_New_Jersey)) (Central Avenue), and [County Route 644](/County_Route_644_(Hudson_County,_New_Jersey)) (Oakland Street). [2]

Its encounter with Concord Street offers a brief moment of choice: an eastbound left lane exit for those seeking an early departure, and a westbound intersection for those arriving. The climax of the upper level's independent existence arrives after its intersection with [Palisade Avenue](/Palisade_Avenue_(Hudson_Palisades)). Here, the upper level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) performs its final act of self-reconciliation, splitting and merging with its lower counterpart. This reunion is facilitated by a westbound ramp, which thoughtfully includes a westbound entrance from the more localized Hoboken Avenue, and a corresponding eastbound ramp. [2] [9] A complex ballet of concrete, designed to shunt you precisely where you need to be, whether you like it or not.

### Viaducts

Ah, the [viaducts](/Viaducts). The very word conjures images of grand Roman engineering, not necessarily these two-story concrete behemoths. Specifically, the four-lane 12th Street and 14th Street structures, completed in 1927 and 1951 respectively – because why build them at the same time when you can stagger the inconvenience? These elevated pathways shoulder the burden of what is effectively Upper [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), stretching from Jersey Avenue at [Boyle Plaza](/Boyle_Plaza) to the geological incision known as the [cut](/Cut_(earthmoving)) into [Bergen Hill](/Bergen_Hill), just beneath [Palisade Avenue](/Palisade_Avenue_(Hudson_Palisades)). [8] [10]

From the western terminus of the 12th Street Viaduct, a series of ramps ascend, connecting to the upper level roadway at the very crest of Bergen Hill, precisely at the Palisade Avenue intersection. The westbound ramp, on the north side, maintains a dignified separation from the main highway, buffered by a formidable reinforced concrete [retaining wall](/Retaining_wall). Conversely, the eastbound ramp, on the south side, is elegantly supported by a series of reinforced concrete deck [arch](/Arch) spans, a touch of structural artistry in an otherwise utilitarian landscape. [8] The western end of the 12th Street Viaduct performs a rather neat trick, transitioning from two-way traffic to a dedicated, four-lane eastbound flow, just east of its crucial connection with the westbound 14th Street Viaduct. [4]

In a move that surprises absolutely no one, the [NJDOT](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) eventually deemed it necessary to throw $92 million at a project to 'renew' these viaducts. [11] The official justification? They were, in the charmingly understated language of bureaucracy, 'structurally deficient'. [12] Which, for those of us who prefer plain English, means they were falling apart. The steel beams, it seems, had succumbed to the relentless march of time and corrosion, while the concrete had become, rather ironically, 'just extra weight'. [13] The ambitious project, designed to avert total collapse, encompassed a full replacement of the concrete deck, a rather optimistic retrofitting for potential earthquakes (because why not?), comprehensive repairs to both the [substructure](/Superstructure) and [superstructure](/Superstructure), and, as a bonus, the construction of a much-needed [shoulder](/Shoulder_(road)) on the westbound 14th Street Viaduct. [11] And, in a final flourish of civic pride, the rehabilitated viaducts were even slated to feature 'ornamental designs' – because nothing says 'historical significance' like a few decorative motifs on a crumbling overpass. [13] This grand undertaking was, by some miracle, declared 'completed' in 2010. [11] One can almost hear the collective sigh of relief, or perhaps just the ongoing rumble of traffic.

### I-78 concurrency

[[Boyle Plaza just after the merge with eastbound Route 139 and I-78]]
And now, for the grand finale: the [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) [concurrency](/Concurrency_(road)). It’s here that the elevated westbound [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) makes its rather dramatic exit from the 14th Street Viaduct of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), a mere block west of Jersey Avenue. Conversely, a dedicated viaduct for eastbound Interstate 78 gracefully parallels the south side of the eastern section of the 12th Street Viaduct. The convergence point, the ultimate meeting of these two titans of transit, occurs where the highway merges with [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) at the eastern terminus of the 12th Street Viaduct. [14]

From this point of no return, [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) continues its eastward march, now in a rather intimate [concurrency](/Concurrency_(road)) with [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey). This combined entity slices through various business districts, manifesting as a quintessential [one-way pair](/One-way_pair): six-lane 12th Street diligently carries eastbound traffic, while six-lane 14th Street handles the westbound flow. This particular segment, a crucial bottleneck for the region, falls under the watchful, if sometimes indifferent, eye of the [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey). This area, a gateway to the subterranean, is also known, rather grandly, as [Boyle Plaza](/Holland_Tunnel). [3]

The first significant encounter along this shared path is with Jersey Avenue, a thoroughfare that graciously leads the way to the urban landscapes of [Downtown Jersey City](/Downtown_Jersey_City) and the decidedly less gritty [Hoboken](/Hoboken,_New_Jersey). [14] Next, it crosses paths with the one-way northbound County Route 633 (Erie Street) next before crossing one-way southbound [County Route 635](/County_Route_635_(Hudson_County,_New_Jersey)) (Grove Street). After Grove Street, the road crosses County Route 637 ([Luis Muñoz Marín](/Luis_Mu%C3%B1oz_Mar%C3%ADn) Boulevard), a notable landmark near the sprawling [Newport Centre Mall](/Newport_Centre_Mall) just to the south. Past this intersection, the eastbound traffic finds itself at the doorstep of the former toll plaza for the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel). From this point, the combined might of the concurrency plunges headfirst into the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) itself, beneath the vast expanse of the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River). This engineering marvel, a testament to human persistence, carries two lanes of traffic in each direction. [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) unceremoniously terminates at the invisible boundary marking the New Jersey and [New York](/New_York_(state)) state line within the tunnel, leaving [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_(New_York)) to continue its solitary, if rather congested, journey into the heart of [New York City](/New_York_City). [3] [14]

A fascinating detail, and one that speaks volumes about perceived importance, is that throughout this entire [I-78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) [concurrency](/Concurrency_(road)) leading to the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel), the road is *never* signed as [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)). It's as if its identity is temporarily suspended, or perhaps deemed irrelevant. The first time the 'Route 139' designation reappears for westbound traffic is at the very moment it splits from [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey), a fleeting acknowledgment. Similarly, for eastbound travelers, its last visible sign is just before it merges with [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey). Even on the New York side, as one approaches the tunnel, [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_(New_York)) is prominently signed, but [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) remains a ghost, an uncredited co-star in its own drama. [14] A stark reminder that some paths are simply more prestigious than others, even if they lead to the same destination.

