Before it became the rather uninspired [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) we know today, the lower level of this highway was once the ambitious, northernmost segment of the [Route 1 Extension](/Route_25_(New_Jersey)). This grand vision was brought forth by the [New Jersey Legislature](/New_Jersey_Legislature) in 1922, with the explicit aim of stretching the existing Route 1 from the venerable city of [Elizabeth](/Elizabeth,_New_Jersey) all the way to the burgeoning gateway of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) in [Jersey City](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey). [16] When the [U.S. Highway System](/U.S._Highway_System) was formally established in 1926 – a bureaucratic triumph, no doubt – this very road was granted the auspicious designation as part of [U.S. Route 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_New_Jersey). [17] However, the fickle hand of progress, or perhaps just a committee with too much time, intervened. In the [1927 New Jersey state highway renumbering](/1927_New_Jersey_state_highway_renumbering), this highway was absorbed into the broader identity of [Route 25](/New_Jersey_Route_25), a route conceived to span the distance from the iconic [Ben Franklin Bridge](/Ben_Franklin_Bridge) in [Camden](/Camden,_New_Jersey) to the very mouth of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel). [18] [19]

[[View east along the lower level of Route 139 just after passing under CR 501 (JFK Boulevard) in Jersey City]]

The identity crisis continued. In the [1953 state highway renumbering](/1953_New_Jersey_state_highway_renumbering), the Route 25 designation for this specific segment was discarded, replaced by the more cumbersome U.S. Route 1/9 Business. This applied to the stretch from the majestic [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway) over [Tonnele Circle](/Tonnele_Circle) all the way to the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel). [20] It wasn't until the 1990s, when grunge was in and sensible road names were out, that U.S. Route 1/9 Business was finally renumbered, mercifully simplifying its existence to the current [NJ Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)). [21] [22] A testament to its enduring, if somewhat convoluted, history, most of the [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) lower level, alongside the magnificent [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway), was recognized as a [contributing property](/Contributing_property) to the Route 1 Extension [historic district](/Historic_district), earning its place on both the [state](/New_Jersey_Register_of_Historic_Places) and [federal](/National_Register_of_Historic_Places) registers of historic places in 2005. [8] [15] Because sometimes, even a road deserves a trophy for merely existing for so long.

Adding another layer to this infrastructural tapestry, the Newark Bay Extension of the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike), primarily serving as the path for [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey), was inaugurated in 1956. Its primary purpose? To provide a direct, high-speed connection from the turnpike straight to the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel). [23] This strategic connection necessitated the designation of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) and [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) as [concurrent](/Concurrency_(road)) routes, effectively merging their paths at the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) approach near Jersey Avenue, a shared journey that extends all the way to the New York state line within the tunnel itself. [1] [3]

### Holland Tunnel and Pulaski Skyway connections

The construction of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) was, as you might imagine, not a simple affair. It necessitated a rather significant urban overhaul, specifically the widening of four crucial blocks of 12th and 14th Streets in [Jersey City](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey), extending from Jersey Avenue to Provost Street. This was a joint effort, a collaborative venture between the New Jersey Interstate Bridge and Tunnel Commission and the New York State Bridge and Tunnel Commission – because apparently, one commission isn't enough to widen a few streets. 12th Street, west of Grove Street, was expanded to a generous 100 feet (30 m), while the final block, the one leading directly to the [toll plaza](/Toll_road), ballooned to an impressive 160 feet (49 m). Similarly, 14th Street and the two blocks of Jersey Avenue, which funneled westbound traffic onto the 12th Street [Viaduct](/Viaduct), were also expanded to 100 feet (30 m). A lot of concrete, a lot of disruption, all for the sake of getting people from one place to another slightly faster.

The original two-way, 12th Street [Viaduct](/Viaduct) from Jersey Avenue to the top of [Bergen Hill](/Bergen_Hill) made its grand debut on July 4, 1927. [10] A fitting date for a new piece of American infrastructure, I suppose. Then, decades later, on February 13, 1951, the four-lane, westbound, 1,800-foot (550 m) 14th Street Viaduct was unveiled, meticulously connected to its 12th Street predecessor. This later addition was a brainchild of the [Port of New York Authority](/Port_of_New_York_Authority), the entity that, having superseded the original state tunnel commissions, assumed control of the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) in 1930. [24] Their motivation for constructing the 14th Street Viaduct was pragmatic: to bypass the awkward turns to and from Jersey Avenue, streamlining the flow of traffic. However, in a classic jurisdictional hand-off, authority over this new viaduct was promptly transferred to the New Jersey State Highway Commission. [25] To accommodate these evolving traffic patterns, the western end of the 12th Street Viaduct, once a two-way affair, was ingeniously reconfigured to handle one-way, four-lane eastbound traffic, specifically just east of its crucial connection with the new westbound 14th Street Viaduct. [8] And, never one to miss an opportunity for expansion, its southern side was further widened between span numbers 1-24 on the eastern end in 1956, a strategic move to facilitate the merge with the eastbound [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike) extension – the very path of [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey). [8]

[[The upper level of Route 139 westbound]]

In 1928, a significant milestone was reached with the opening of the completed lower level portion of the highway. This, coupled with the [Route 1 Extension](/Route_25_(New_Jersey)) on the eastern side of the [Passaic River](/Passaic_River), marked the initial phase of what was envisioned as a high-speed connection between the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) and the bustling hub of [Newark](/Newark,_New_Jersey). [26] Concurrently, the upper level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), known as the Hoboken Avenue Viaduct, also opened its lanes, providing a multi-lane thoroughfare that stretched from [Palisades Avenue](/Palisade_Avenue_(Hudson_Palisades)) to [John F. Kennedy Boulevard](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)). [8]

The grand design for a high-speed [freeway](/Controlled-access_highway) connection finally reached its zenith with the much-anticipated opening of the iconic [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway) in 1932. The original Pulaski Skyway ramp at its eastern terminus, proving insufficient for the ever-increasing demands of traffic, was eventually supplanted by two elongated, external ramps. These new structures were meticulously dedicated to managing the eastbound and westbound flows of traffic, originating from the dramatic [cut](/Cut_(earthmoving)) in [Bergen Hill](/Bergen_Hill), just west of [John F. Kennedy Boulevard](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)). [8] Further refining the network, on September 14, 1938, a direct ramp, famously known as the Tonnele Circle Viaduct, was inaugurated. This elegant solution soared over [Tonnele Circle](/Tonnele_Circle) itself, specifically designed to funnel westbound traffic directly onto southbound [U.S. Route 1/9 Truck](/U.S._Route_1-9_Truck), a route that, with impressive alacrity, links to [Route 7](/New_Jersey_Route_7) and ultimately to [Interstate 280](/Interstate_280_(New_Jersey)). [8] Efficiency, or at least the illusion of it, was paramount.

### Later years

[[View eastbound along Route 139 from Palisade Avenue, with the Jersey City and Manhattan skylines visible ahead]]

The late 20th century, ever eager for new infrastructure, saw the proposal of the Bergen Arches Expressway in 1989 by Governor [Thomas Kean](/Thomas_Kean). The idea was to forge a vital connection between the burgeoning [Jersey City](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey) waterfront and a new railroad line, a line that would, in turn, provide access to the illustrious [Meadowlands Sports Complex](/Meadowlands_Sports_Complex). This ambitious four-lane road was designed to trace the path of an abandoned railroad line, quaintly known as the [Bergen Arches](/Bergen_Arches). [27] The concept found a fervent champion in Jersey City Mayor [Bret Schundler](/Bret_Schundler), who, with admirable foresight, believed such a highway would not only spur further development but also offer much-needed relief to the perpetually congested, four-lane [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)). The project even managed to secure a hefty $26 million allocation in 1998, courtesy of the federal [Transportation Equity Act for the 21st Century](/Transportation_Equity_Act_for_the_21st_Century). [28] However, the winds of political will are notoriously fickle. By 2001, both leading candidates for Jersey City mayor had, perhaps wisely, shifted their support towards a transit line along the Bergen Arches, rather than another highway. [29] And so, in 2002, the plans for a highway along the Bergen Arches were unceremoniously abandoned, as Jersey City leaders, including Mayor [Glenn Dale Cunningham](/Glenn_Dale_Cunningham), definitively threw their weight behind mass transit. [30] A rare victory for public transport, one might observe.

Fast forward to 2011, and we encounter a truly 'controversial' maneuver by Governor [Chris Christie](/Chris_Christie). He famously directed the [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) to reallocate funds – funds originally designated for the rather important [Access to the Region's Core](/Access_to_the_Region%27s_Core) rail project – towards highway projects instead. The Port Authority, ever compliant, consented to contribute a cool $1.8 billion. This sum was intended to partially finance the 'rehabilitation' of the [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway) and [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)), among other projects deemed essential to the broader distribution network within the colossal [Port of New York and New Jersey](/Port_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey). [31] [32] [33] Because, naturally, roads are always more urgent than trains, especially when they funnel directly into a port.

The [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) project itself involved a series of meticulous interventions. The eastbound side of the Hoboken Avenue Viaduct underwent a thorough rehabilitation, while the westbound roadway received a fresh resurfacing. Furthermore, 'operational improvements' – a vague but reassuring term – were implemented at several intersections on the upper roadway, necessitating the replacement of all existing overpasses. [34] The project also included the crucial replacement of the deck and a comprehensive rehabilitation of the [superstructure](/Superstructure) of the Conrail Viaduct. The total estimated cost of this extensive undertaking was a staggering $180–200 million, with an initial completion target of 2016. [5] [33] [35] Of course, in the grand tradition of public works, this deadline was later, and predictably, pushed back to 2019. [36] The [Pulaski Skyway](/Pulaski_Skyway) eventually reopened its lanes in mid-2018, [37] and the lower level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) enjoyed a brief, temporary restoration to its full four-lane capacity in December 2018, only to be partially closed *again* in early 2019. [36] [38] Such is the cyclical nature of infrastructure. Nevertheless, by 2019, the lower level of [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) did receive some tangible enhancements, including much-needed new lighting and updated pavement markings. [39] Small mercies, I suppose.

In a more recent development, the section of 12th Street east of Marin Boulevard, which serves as the eastbound artery for both [Interstate 78](/Interstate_78_in_New_Jersey) and [Route 139](/Route_139_(New_Jersey_state_highway)) towards the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel) in [Jersey City](/Jersey_City,_New_Jersey), underwent a curious transformation. It was narrowed from six to four lanes. This reduction occurred after the implementation of [open road tolling](/Open_road_tolling) was [implemented](/Holland_Tunnel) at the [Holland Tunnel](/Holland_Tunnel), presumably to streamline flow, or perhaps just to confuse drivers further. [40] And, as if history repeats itself with a slightly different twist, in 2025, the [United States Department of Transportation](/United_States_Department_of_Transportation) saw fit to award a $25 million grant to the [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) specifically to *further* narrow the stretch of 12th Street between Jersey Avenue and Marin Boulevard. [40] [41] Because if at first you don't succeed in narrowing, try, try again, with more federal money.

